    <p>SUBARU</p>
    <p>For­get about the Forester Ul­ti­mate Cus­tomised Kit Spe­cial edi­tion al­ready.</p>
    <p>In the se­cond quar­ter of the year, Subaru will have an all-new Out­back (left). The rugged wagon, avail­able as a pre­mium 2.5i-Tour­ing vari­ant, prom­ises improved han­dling and sta­bil­ity as well as bet­ter fuel ef­fi­ciency and power.</p>
    <p>In the fourth quar­ter, we will see the new BRZ (be­low left), the se­cond it­er­a­tion of a sporty coupe de­vel­oped by Subaru and Toy­ota. En­dowed with an even lower cen­tre of grav­ity than the first BRZ (sup­pos­edly on a par with some su­per­cars), it prom­ises improved han­dling.</p>
    <p>With a new low-sit­ting 2.4-litre nat­u­rally as­pi­rated en­gine, it prom­ises more oomph, too.</p>
    <p>Suzuki’s first hy­brid here will be the Swift Sport Hy­brid, which is ex­pected in the se­cond half of the year.</p>
    <p>It is in­ter­est­ing that it is the hot hatch vari­ant which gets elec­tric as­sis­tance. But be­fore you get too ex­cited, it is ac­tu­ally a “mild hy­brid” with a 48-volt starter­gen­er­a­tor that gives the car a small shove from the lights and which re­cov­ers en­ergy lost in brak­ing.</p>


